title: Ben Reacts to Abortion Debate Between Dr. Phil and Lila Rose
CommentTitle:
The woman in the audience berated Lila Rose for a supposed lack of empathy.  This is grossly hypocritical.  Ignoring the very obvious fact that this is a personal attack which is a defining aspect of pro-abortion extremism, the woman herself fails to show any empathy, care or concern for the unborn female individual whose life she is happy to see snuffed out for the "crime" of being unplanned, inconvenient or not being "perfect".  The lives of individual females can live without her ideology; literally.

Finally, to correct the misinformation stated  by Dr. Phil, nonsense arguments suggesting a lack of medical consensus are spurious.  To clarify, the switch to distinct biological human life is turned on at conception with the introduction of a diploid set of 46 human chromosomes.  Gamete cells join to produce somatic cells which adopt one set of chromosomes from each parent, 23 derived from the ovum (the egg) and 23 derived from the sperm and so, fertilisation can be said to end with the creation of the single-cell zygote. 

From a biological viewpoint, human life is not static; rather it is one continuous ageing process of biological and personal development. From this moment on, every human life has two fundamental requirements, namely a safe environment and also adequate and appropriate sustenance. title: Responding to Chrissy Teigen's Viral Abortion Controversy
CommentTitle: I had a subchorionic hemmorhage at 11 weeks, then 13 weeks.  I bled and bled through the entire pregnancy.  It was scary. I prayed, and saw my doctor frequently.  My baby held on.  He was born prematurely at 32 weeks, after my water broke.  His placenta was gray and looked like chewed meat.  He is now 6'3" and a brilliant young man. He is an amazing soul --- a true miracle.  Don't give up, moms.  Miracles do happen.  The body will let you know.  My blood pressure stayed fine and I was monitored. I lost blood, but I rested and continued.  We can do amazing things.  I wasn't about to give up without a fight. However, NO judgement --- as I don't know their specific circumstances.  No one told me I'd die if I didn't abort.  But if my baby started to die in the womb, or my life was at risk, it would become clear and evident -- a natural process no one would feel guilty for or need to "figure out"/explain/euphemize to the world.  Sad it had to be turned into a spectacle.  Peace to their family.

title: Responding to Chrissy Teigen's Viral Abortion Controversy
CommentTitle: I am unbelieveable disgusted.  As a woman who made the WRONG decision 20 years ago please please please any woman who reads this, learn from ME.  20 years ago i had 3 small children and my husband literally left us in the middle of the night, moved to a differeny state.  Me and my kids woke up to my husbnad, their father gone.  he was the primary bread winner and I was only making $9,00 an hour part time.  We had just bought a home and had a car that ended up getting repo'd.  He didn't help us for a long time and even then it wasn't much. .  about a month after he left I found out i was pregnant and told him, he stated that "i dont' care it is probably not mine". of course it was his and he didn‚Äôt care.   I was scared, young, and alone.  I had no one and barely able to feed my kids some nights. I went several nights not eating to assure my kids did. I felt alone, and didn't think I had a choice. I remember making the appt and then I went into this cold room and was treated like It was just another procedure like getting a tooth pulled. I remember crying saying "wait a minute" and they didn't,  I had medicine put into my vein and I was awake but loopy.  It was horrible, it was the worst thing I have ever gone through in my life.  I realized my poor baby was gone, thrown away like they were nothing and i did it. that was 20 years ago and I haven't gotten over it.  I have prayed and prayed for forgiveness even though I don't deserve it. I talk to my child and say daily I am sorry, I love you I was wrong. I live in this hell everyday and I deserve too.  I am now older, I know now it would have worked out and I wish I could go back and tell the younger self so many thngs.  I am divorced from him thank God .. a few years later I had a still born and i thought God punished me for what I did.  Then when I was 31 I found out I had uterine cancer, and had a hysterectomy. That was my punishment. I deserved it,  I know God has forgiven me but I can't forgive myself. did i get cancer because of what i did ? Did my daughter die because of what i did?  every day I miss my baby i threw away and I will never ever forget.  I pray one day God will allow me to see him/her in heaven and I pray that he/she is up there playing with her sister.  So please any woman readhing this, learn from me, listen to me don't kill your baby please.  I love you my previous angel and one day I pray God lets me hold you and hug you,.. love mommy

title: The Economy Is Spiraling The Drain
CommentTitle:
7:35 What Ben is failing to realize here is that your grandpa working a hard job riveting (which is probably much more mentally rewarding because physical work is like that for a lot of men) could actually afford to support a family of 7 and pay off his mortgage, all on a single income, while his wife took care of children and the home. You can't even get close to that on an average construction wage in almost any country today. Especially not in a developed nation. The cost of living for basics is higher, and the ratio of salary to the cost of a house is between 2-3 times higher than the ratio our grandpa was facing. Meaning you have to have more money saved for a deposit and a longer time to pay off a house.

Mobile phones and uber eats aren't arguments for a better time to live in Ben. Especially mobile phones. It is essentially compulsory for adults to have one nowadays to live in society. If you don't you couldn't even access most of the services provided nowadays. This also means you have a phone bill, essentially compulsory. Try riding a bus or applying for a job without at least a mobile phone or laptop with an internet connection nowadays.

What makes life for people worth living is an upward trajectory. Something our grandpa had, but I don't think many/most people feel as though they have today.

title: To Push Abortion, The Left Promotes A Fetal Heartbeat Hoax |¬†Ep. 1581
CommentTitle:
My wife and I were trying desperately to have our first child. Ultimately, we wound up going the In-vitro route. At precisely 6 weeks after conception (well documented, to say the least), my wife had a ‚Äúbleeding event‚Äù on a Friday evening. We spent that night at our local ER. The bleeding stopped, but the ER‚Äôs ultrasound equipment was not sophisticated enough to tell us anything about the pregnancy. We were told to follow up with our specialist on Monday morning.

I was stressed, but still hopeful. All the doctors and medical professionals told us that some bleeding is not uncommon, and otherwise everything looked good.

Then my wife had another bleeding event on Sunday afternoon. She was devastated. And while I remained positive and supportive on the outside for my wife, inside, I was devastated as well. Instead of going to the ER, we decided to wait until the next morning to see our In-Vitro specialist. Based on our experience earlier in the weekend, we would get answers just as fast this way.

We went to the doctor‚Äôs office the next morning really just expecting to confirm our worst fears. The doctor was very professional and supportive, but you could tell she shared our outlook. Again, this was right at six weeks. The doctor was performing the ultrasound, saying things like ‚ÄúOkay, that looks healthy, but I don‚Äôt see it there.‚Äù She did this a few times, when suddenly, the nurse assisting her called out loudly: ‚ÄúWAIT! What was that?!? Was that a heartbeat!?!‚Äù The doctor was like ‚ÄúWHERE?‚Äù and went back to the spot she had just been examining. And there, sure enough, was a little, pulsating, strong, fast, tiny heartbeat. Our worst fears vanished, washed completely away by the strongest feelings of joy and love that I have personally ever experienced. There was not a dry eye in that office after that.

Again, at just six weeks.

F*** you, Stacey Abrams.

title: To Push Abortion, The Left Promotes A Fetal Heartbeat Hoax |¬†Ep. 1581
CommentTitle: Veteran ultrasound technologist here. Yes, fetal cardiac activity CAN be detected at 6 weeks. There are 2 techniques we use to sample it. Spectral Doppler which detects velocities of blood flow and or motion. The frequency shift that is detected with spectral Doppler is reflected in an auditory sound which is what people hear as a heart beat. We don't use this at 6 weeks mainly because it's a much stronger sound wave and although there isn't much evidence for it, can cause cavitation on sensitive tissue. The other technique we use is M-mode. Which only detects motion. This doesn't emit an auditory sound. So depending on which stage of pregnancy we perform an exam on a fetus determines whether or not you can actually hear the heart beat. This is basic  physics. But I wouldn't expect this failed politician to actually know what facts are.

CommentTitle:
Bro‚Ä¶I generally try to be compassionate towards homeless people and give them a dollar or two, because I imagine that if I were ever in that situation I‚Äôd probably want some people to be kind to me too.  
That being said, it‚Äôs tough to not be critical when I see the same homeless woman every other night at the gas station that just needs $15 for a hotel room or the same dude on the same intersection corner for six months or the guy that manages to ask before you go in to a store/restaurant that he only needs $10 to get some gas for his broke down car.  After giving him $5 we come back out 2 hrs later and he still just needs $10 for gas to get wherever he‚Äôs trying to go.  
I had a lady one time tell me a story about how her daughter was just shot by her deadbeat boyfriend and she was in the hospital and tears were welling up in her eyes, it was very touching and I think I gave her like $20 to get to the hospital.  Well two days later at another gas station a few miles down the road, the same woman with the same story and the tears and everything, I asked her if she remembered me, she just kept right on with her story until I asked exactly when her daughter was shot, today she said and I told her she had the worst luck to have two daughters both shot by their boyfriends in the same week.  Tears stopped immediately and the confusion set in.  
The problem with scam artists is that they ruin it for the people that truly just need some help, but I always tell myself it‚Äôs not on me after I‚Äôve tried to help. Anyways, sorry for the long rant but that‚Äôs a few of my experiences with the matter

CommentTitle:
I remember in the 1970s (I'm old) when the predictions were for a coming ice age.  And I remember that then the predictions stopped.   I remember, though, the alarmism that was fostered.   Then I got older, and in high school, I started learning about computers and such.   And I learned about data, and trying to run computer programs with too much data, too much information to process.  And somewhere along the way, I realised that the government likes to foster fear.   Because if people are afraid, they're more likely to trust their leaders.   Which meant I was skeptical about Global Warming, as it was first called, from almost the beginning.   And then we get a certain vice-president going around telling people that they have to stop using fossil fuels, OR ELSE!!!   But he was traveling around in his PERSONAL JET, burning all kinds of fossil fuel, to go places.   Classic "do as I say, not as I do".

We're headed for an ice age:   we need more government control of our lives to combat it; we're headed for global warming: we need more government control of our lives to combat it.   Science can't even tell us for certain if it's going to rain tomorrow, just give us a percentage likelihood.

And if f---ing Dick Durbin tells me the sky will be blue tomorrow, I'm going to expect it to be red.

I won't say Climate Change isn't happening.   Climate Change is just weather.  And to deny humanity affecting the weather would be silly.   But Earth has warming and cooling trends.   How do we tell how much of a trend is man made, and how much is reversible?   How do we know that melting ice caps won't f--- up the gulf stream and other undersea currents?   How do we know that global warming won't lead to global cooling?

I don't trust the scientists' climate models to be overly relalistic.   I don't trust the government to try to sew fear just to keep their jobs, and gain more power over others.   I won't deny climate change, but I'm going to take it with a grain of sand the size of Hillary Clinton's ego.

CommentTitle:
The problem with assuming "regulated" means regulated by the government, is the moment a militia has to obey the government, it ceases to be a militia. A militia is a civilian fighting force. Forces that answer to and are beholden to the government are not civilian forces, they are government forces.

So the very use of the word "militia" means "regulated," by context, is referring to being functional. Like keeping your bowels regular. To be in good working condition.

Obviously, if a civilian fighting force is to be in working order, capable of resisting tyranny, the people must have the right to keep/own and bear armaments that will make them capable of going toe-to-toe with tyrants, be those tyrants foreign or domestic.

This is really simple shit; the founding fathers intentionally worded the Bill of Rights to be read AND UNDERSTOOD by the layman. There is no nuance to it, it says exactly what it means, especially given the historical context in which it was written.

CommentTitle: Red dots absolutely help make shooting easier once you learn to use them properly. I find that it‚Äôs easier to make hits with red dots for newer people because they want to remain target focused anyway, but it can be a bit of a learning curve for someone used to irons because they‚Äôll try to focus on the dot. The flip side of the red dot vs irons argument is that your presentation needs to be more consistent. I‚Äôve noticed myself focusing on the dot before and am still drilling it into myself to focus on the target, but once you do maintain target focus, it does make it easier to make hits especially on smaller targets that aren‚Äôt standing out as much. I grew up with only irons or a scoped rifle and there definitely is a learning curve on red dots but I feel that the learning curve is not too bad and is definitely worth it.

Canada does actually have a legal document that enshrine personal liberties similar to the US Constitution (First Amendment, etc.).

- Ability to bind and release energy

title: GUN WEEK w/ Mrgunsngear | Ep 2. Long Guns 101
CommentTitle:
For those looking for a decent first AR and Handgun, look up the Palmetto State Armory PA-15 and Dagger. They are the two most widely available weapons platforms on the US market. 

The PA15 comes in multiple configurations, and sometimes if you buy the upper and lower separate, you can catch a deal to get 10x 30rd magazines with the upper receiver. 

As for the Dagger, it has recently gotten a lot of attention due to PSA utilizing the Glock 19 Gen 3 design and making a reliable pistol for a fraction of the cost (the trigger is the main corner-cut, but it works fine and is easily replaced for a better trigger unit). On top of that, the Dagger comes available with a threaded barrel and cut outs for red dot sights. (And sometimes even comes with a Holosun red dot pre-installed)

CommentTitle: Having the unfortunate occurrence of having been homeless in a very liberal city, I think I can add to this topic. I was DUMPED in Los Angeles after being physically ill overseas. YES, substance abuse and mental illness are MAJOR causes. But, there are other groups. There are people, like me, who were physically ill. There are people who just fell on hard times. i.e. lost jobs or housing. There are MANY alcoholics and addicts. Mental illness in many forms. Not just schizophrenia. The last group, some might classify as "mentally ill" but, aren't what many would automatically think of. Those who just want to be "left alone". Wanting no responsibilities like paying rent or bills. These are usually older people who were productive and have basically decided to just want to drop out of society. Lastly, on the topic of homelessness, liberals talk a good game but, they do ABSOLUTELY NOTHING to assist the homeless!!! They NEVER try to help anyone find a job. In fact, many homeless services, like shelters, will PUNISH you for having the audacity to find employment! I have witnessed it first hand. People who have found a job, started the new job and, having the homeless shelter take away their bed because of it!!!! I saw that several times, Needless to say, if a person has to sleep on a sidewalk, keeping a job becomes quite difficult.

(NerdWallet) ‚Äì Need something to be thankful for? Well, in addition to the roof above your head and the device you‚Äôre reading this on, you can add the price of your Thanksgiving turkey to the list.

That‚Äôs according to the American Farm Bureau Federation (AFBF), which found that the average price of an 8-to-16-pound turkey was $1.27 per pound in August 2023 ‚Äî a 22% decline from August 2022. The U.S. Department of Agriculture likewise lists the average price per pound for frozen, whole hen turkeys as $1.27 in August 2023 ‚Äî down just over 22% from $1.64 in August 2022.

The prices of some turkey products fell more dramatically, like boneless and skinless male turkey breasts, which were 61% cheaper in August 2023 than the same time last year, per the AFBF.

The International Criminal Court (ICC or ICCt) is an intergovernmental organization and international tribunal seated in The Hague, Netherlands. It is the first and only permanent international court with jurisdiction to prosecute individuals for the international crimes of genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes and the crime of aggression. It is distinct from the International Court of Justice, an organ of the United Nations that hears disputes between states.

The ICC began operations on 1 July 2002, upon the entry into force of the Rome Statute, a multilateral treaty that serves as the court's charter and governing document. States which become party to the Rome Statute become members of the ICC, serving on the Assembly of States Parties, which administers the court. As of March 2022, there are 123 ICC member states; 42 states have neither signed nor become parties to the Rome Statute.

Russia and the US are NOT members!

CommentTitle: I was visiting Portland last year with my wife to see my brother. My wife and I were taking public bus transportation and as I ran to flag the bus I came close to a homeless man with his bed on the sidewalk. I stopped suddenly to not mess with his space and jogged around him to catch the bus. All of a sudden I was pushed violently from behind by this man and he began yelling unintelligible garbage at me and began advancing toward me. I raised my hands and firmly said no! He stopped short of me still yelling at me. I turned away again and crossed crossed the street toward my bus. I didn't know if he was armed and definitely felt scared to be attacked in broad daylight. I do not feel safe in Portland and don't want to go back.

CommentTitle:
I live in California. My city has a pretty good sized homeless population. I drove past it, a few days ago, as I crossed my town.  It's moved from a 'safe' sidewalk to spaces lining the railroad tracks.  Seriously, between the wire fence and the actual tracks.  It's so sad, and potentially dangerous.

I think we have such a large homeless population, in California, because we have less drastic weather extremes.  I'm sure other 'warmer' states have the same issue.

While I do not have the answer, as to how to resolve the homeless situation, I do wonder if we did not send so much money, to resolve other country's issues, if we couldn't improve conditions in our own country.  Then again, maybe those in charge do not want to.  That might mean less money for their personal agendas/pockets.

title: Rich Lowry | The Ben Shapiro Show Sunday Special Ep. 77
CommentTitle: Rich Lowery definitely seems like an establishment guy. He can point at the correct issues, but the paradigm he uses for them seem completely off. His views on nationalism and comparing our creeds to be similar to European creeds is completely incorrect when it comes to the placement of sovereignty, ie. in the individual, the masses, or the state. America is a land and a creed, as shown by the spread of our ideas outward, albeit those notions have been sometimes corrupted to further local agendas. He places too much emphasis on the land and not the founding ideas. Secondly, Lowery criticizes Trump about not being strong enough on the events of extremists in Charlottesville, yet laments the othering of people living in the conditions in Baltimore. At face value it fair, but contextualy it shows an incongruous understanding of the message. Baltimore's highlight ended up sparking a grassroots movement to clean up the town. It was empowering to the people. Trump's statement on Charlottesville is completely correct because he was condemning the extremists yet acknowledging the sentiment that ended up being hijacked. This was revealed by Lowery's stance on the Confederate flag and statues, which was to simply run away from the topic.

title: The Only 3 Things We Need To Know About Immigration
CommentTitle: I agreed with 90% of what she said. I am currently patiently waiting in Peru for almost 18 months to get my green card (my husband is a U.S citizen sponsoring me) and we are doing the legal process for 3 reasons: 1) We respect laws, 2) we have the economic resources to do so, and 3) my life is not in danger in Peru. But if my life was in danger, I didn‚Äôt have the economic resources to apply for asylum from my country, and I have to make a decision fast before I get killed, I would escape my country, not necessarily to America, but I have to go somewhere else to stay alive. So I understand why so many poor immigrants that are unsafe in their countries end up escaping to another one, even if that means breaking that country‚Äôs law; in Peru we are dealing with that right now with Venezuelans refugees. Simultaneously, I agree that America, or any other country for that matter, has the right to know who enters it, and the problem right now is identifying who is an actual refugee and who is a not.

title: Mass Shooting Safety Expert Breaks Down Scenes From ‚ÄòRun Hide Fight'
CommentTitle:
When I was a student, the emergency drills were done on a monthly basis and during different periods so that students would know how to handle themselves in classrooms at different parts of the campus that evacuated to different locations. 

Now, schools will often do the minimal requirement only during the periods before nutrition or lunch, and give teachers advance notice of which period the procedure would take place.  Often I would have one or two students that would not meet back up with my class at the rendezvous point and would either hold back my attendance to the administrator or list missing students.  Often students would be released to nutrition or lunch before these students were accounted for.

I always try to bring someone close to me, preferably someone I live with and/or interact with regularly-- because I *know* that I am often not aware of whether my mentaal state has shifted, whereas someone around me can say, "yeah, you've been much more irritable than usual lately" or "I've noticed you've been much more motivated than before [insert current treatment plan]."

title: Welfare For the Upper Class | The Matt Walsh Show Ep. 407
CommentTitle: While I agree that outright college loan "forgiveness" is welfare for the upper class, I think a more appropriate solution is to allow those loans to be discharged in personal bankruptcy.  Currently student loans are the only type of loans that are not discharged through bankruptcy.  Amend the law to do two things: (1) individuals can discharge their student loan debt through bankruptcy and will take a serious hit to their credit score, and (2) require student loan lenders to discern between applicants--that is, folks entering into a field of study with a higher starting salary (engineering, computers sciences, business, law, medical) will be given more loan access than the useless underwater basketweaving degrees.

CommentTitle:
Hello Ben, when you are cool and level-headed, I really enjoy your angles and analysis. 

This time however, your agitation and frustration clearly is heavily impacting your commentary.   

Anger happens to us all, and as you may know, it distorts and darkens what we see, how we see and what we want to see.  As an influencer, I hope you that to heart.

Comments left by fellow YouTubers show the amount of ill-will stirred up by this video.  In hindsight, reactions instigated by hatred have always been regrettable with blind areas overlooked and painful lessons learned.  

Please be careful about broad sweeping demonizations.  In history, we have seen what happens when such narratives get reinforced.

Let the anger pass. When replaced with empathy, discernment and objectivity, your intellect and eloquence will inspire.

Take care Ben!

CommentTitle:
The premise of a free market economy is that all transactions are consensual and benefit both parties. You give something, usually some money, and receive a good or service in return that you value over the money you just exchanged it for. Meaning, in theory, every single penny Bloomberg has earned in his life is proof of his worthwhile contributions to society. He helped people, and got rich off of it. That sounds like a man that perhaps deserves at least a modicum of consideration for the presidency, certainly more so than the average middle class worker who's barely managing to keep themselves and their family afloat. In the end, people are going to evaluate your potential as president based on your past accomplishments, and I certainly cannot deny Bloomberg is an accomplished man - with a skill set perfectly tailored for the job to boot - even if I happen to wildly disagree with most of his policies. And if he wants to use his own cash to compete in the race, all the more power to him. Or should we complain when rich people pay for stuff they want? Because that is called consensual wealth redistribution my friend, and it's a wonderful thing.


So yeah, if you wanna become president of the most powerful capitalist economy/country in the world, become and exceptionally successful entrepreneur first. Win the free market Olympics and forge yourself into a better person in the process, then have a go at it. But don't become TOO rich and successful if you wanna run democrat, because they'll default to thinking you're Hitler or something. üôÑ

CommentTitle:
It is said that carbon dioxide stands for 14-25 percent of the greenhouse effect. I strongly doubt that it is that much for several reasons (it also defies logic that the 0.04% CO2 would cause as much as 14-25% of the greenhouse effect). 
This means that out of the raise of 0.8-1 degree Celsius since preindustrial times the burning of fossile fuels results in at the most 0.2 degrees Celsius. I'm however pretty sure - for several reasons - that the burning of fossile fuels has resulted in substantially less than a 0.2 degrees Celsius increase of the global temperature during the last 150 years. 
And when you add the fact that the burning of fossile fuels only has added 3-4% (maybe less) of the 0,04% CO2 in the atmosphere, then the burning of coal, oil and gas of - at the very most - the 0.2 degrees becomes much less.
SOURCE: G. A. Schmidt, R. A. Ruedy, R. L. Miller and A. A. Lacis (2010). ‚ÄùAttribution of the present‚Äêday total greenhouse effect‚Äù. J. Geophys. Res., 115, D20106.

CommentTitle:
I use the term conscientious objector.  It harkens back to refusing to fight in war.

I am a 39 year old Marine Corps veteran (02-06) who used my GI Bill to obtain a bachelors in philosophy, a bachelors in psychology, a Masters in cognitive and behavioral neuroscience, then quit my PhD program during the lockdowns.  I have taught undergraduate statistics lectures at an R1 university (a privilege normally reserved for faculty, but there was a gap).  I have studied Hume, Popper, and Kuhn.  I am published in peer reviewed journals.  I know what ethical science looks like... and what it doesn't.  I know what ethical state authority looks like... and what it doesn't.  

I will not knowingly follow unethical orders to do harm to anyone, including myself.  My conscience is enough for me.

title: Watch Climate Protestors Face Real Consequences
CommentTitle: The electric underground train system in London (The Tube) is the most ecological way for people to travel into London (apart from walking or cycling). If the Tube trains are held up for even a few minutes it becomes very dangerous on the platforms, as the crush of people builds up and begins to get forced dangerously towards the edges and the electric rail lines. The Tube trains run every 1 to 2 minutes (from the working-class part of London where this video was shot); as you can see, the crowds were beginning to grow to an unsafe size on the platform. The self-absorbed, Middle class, virtue-signalling Narcissists are despised by the working class in Britain. They should have picked one of the leafier, more prosperous, neo-Liberal parts of London to stage their display of moral superiority and sanctimonious self-righteousness.

title: 'Being gay doesn't make you a refugee!' Andrew Pierce backs Braverman, slams Biden & UN asylum rules
CommentTitle: "Being gay does not make you a refugee."  Correct.  The UN Refugee Convention requires a person to prove a well-founded fear of persecution - NOT discrimination.  Gay people in Iran are thrown off high buildings by state agents.  Andrew Pierce is right - that is persecution.  But merely feeling disadvantaged or discriminated against is not.  Braverman is deliberately misrepresenting what the Convention says in order to distract attention from her utter failure to get a grip on her department.  The fact is that the Home Office is notorious for long delays in assessing asylum applications.  There is now a huge backlog, hence we are spending millions on hotels, barges and the hugely expensive Rwanda scheme.  Of course not everyone who arrives here in a small boat is a genuine refugee.  I suspect most are not.  But until their applications are processed, we don't know who qualifies as a refugee and who does not.  Those who do not need to be identified and removed within weeks, not allowed to live here for two or three years while the Home Office takes its own sweet time.  And what about taking up the French offer of setting up an asylum processing centre there?  Something the government refuses to do.  If you want to find out who is responsible for this shambles, look no further than the Home Secretary.

title: LIVE: Michael Gove and Jenny Harries speak to UK's COVID Inquiry
CommentTitle: Well Mr. Gove, at the time of this virus outbreak, were you or were you not advised by some medical doctors not to use the mRNA vaccine technology as a vaccine against Cov19? Was it clearly explained to you as to why not to use this form of medication and the health problems to be experienced if this mRNA technology was to be used. Well, I gather you were informed, on all accounts, hence chose to ignore the advice and the subsequent health issues proved to be true. Is it also true that the senior government health adviser too was informed, as you were, by these medical doctors. The reply these doctors got, from this government adviser, was that these doctors were spreading conspiracy theories. Well, later that turned out not to be the case. I do believe that this government adviser later picked up a Knighthood, no wonder government refuses to hold a full inquiry in to the whole affair, simply because big heads would roll, what say you Mr.Gove.

title: Ukraine's elite gunners shoot down three Russian Kamikaze drones with anti-aircraft weapons
CommentTitle: What I see no one else commenting on is how they are ingeniously using what appears to be a consumer available handheld miniaturized thermal camera (guy directing the flak gunner, in his left hand) to spot a far away drone. I'm unsure the model but this set up with the pistol grip style holder for the camera is similar to what you see being used for usb phone thermals such as the T2 Pro, etc. Thus, my suspicion that he's using a similar, perhaps Teledyne FLIR product. If that's true, that's a pretty awesome and cost effective way to give ground troops some simple and relatively cheap air defense detection. I am noting this for SHTF scenario.  üòÜ
